                <Description>
            Galaxy IC 5332 was observed as part of the Physics at High Angular resolution in Nearby GalaxieS (PHANGS) program, 
            a large project that includes observations from several space- and ground-based telescopes of many galaxies to 
            help researchers study all phases of the star formation cycle, from the formation of stars within dusty gas clouds 
            to the energy released in the process that creates the intricate structures revealed by Webbâ€™s new images. 
            IC 5332 is 30 million light-years away in the constellation Sculptor. Learn more about what can be seen in this 
            vast collection of Webb images here. 
            [Image description: Webbâ€™s image of IC 5332 shows a densely populated face-on spiral galaxy anchored by a central 
            region that has a light blue haze. Spine-like spiral orange arms extend to the edges and rotate clockwise.]
                </Description>
                <ThumbnailUrl>http://data1.wwtassets.org/packages/2024/01_jwst/weic2403b/thumb.jpg</ThumbnailUrl>
            </ImageSet>
